      "message": "Patch Set 3: No score\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nRequest response to inline comment.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "c7cd2b2bd90b99e95b79112274f5ec7bad161e4f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 291,
        "name": "Chuck Fossen",
        "email": "chuckf@cray.com",
        "username": "chuckf"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-04 18:16:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: No score\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\ncfs_daemonize() calls need to be changed to daemonize().\nAlso, cfs_block_allsigs() can be removed since daemonize already blocks all signals.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "d6d7e7e902aab4a0c12f9ac60fd3ff3236b80f9a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-04 18:36:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\ndaemonize() is only needed when a user-space task does kernel_thread(). Is that the case here?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "5fc297c1091308bfa8194ca01739a4f852bc22b6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-04 18:43:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nThe combo to use for kernel thread is either kernel_thread and daemonize, or use kthread_create/kthread_run. Mixing those up will cause a lot of pain.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "53d7beb594a696afc1563352671cd8e504305019",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 291,
        "name": "Chuck Fossen",
        "email": "chuckf@cray.com",
        "username": "chuckf"
      },
      "date": "2013-09-04 20:37:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nJames, you are correct, we don't need daemonize(). Is the cfs_block_allsigs() going to go away in the future? It also makes kernel calls - sigfillset(). If so, we may as well make the change now.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "50ef658d6650b30bac991995dc24fc737c2f7517",
